37:21.506 --> 37:23.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Let me turn now
to Syria.

37:23.808 --> 37:25.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Initially -- and, of course, it
was a different
government.

37:25.777 --> 37:29.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The government of Egypt opposed
President
Bashar al-Assad.

37:29.180 --> 37:35.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are signs now that, in
fact, the
Egyptian government is growing
closer to him,

37:35.086 --> 37:36.888 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
more supportive.

37:36.921 --> 37:41.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Sisi said he thought
the Assad army
was perhaps best equipped to
fight terrorism.

37:41.860 --> 37:48.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have been also voting with
Russia in the
Security Council on resolutions
related to

37:48.433 --> 37:50.268 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria.

37:50.301 --> 37:55.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the Syrian government asked
Egypt to also
send forces of any kinds, and
there have been

37:55.907 --> 37:59.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
